                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European Advisory Commission/10–1444:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-14T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 14, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 14—2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8743. Comea<note n="3" xml:id="d64fn3">Series designation for telegrams from
                        London dealing with matters before the European Advisory Commission.</note>
                    111. Department’s 8384 [<hi rend="italic">8284</hi>], October 9, 4 p.m. In my
                    opinion it would be a great mistake to introduce the French question into the
                    deliberations of the European Advisory Commission until the basic military
                    papers have been cleared with the Russians and the British.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
